[6] Diarrhea - India (Maharashtra State)
Date: Mon 11 Aug 2014
Source: Times of India, Times News Network (TNN) [edited]
http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/nashik/Diarrhoea-outbreak-in-Niphad-over-250-taken-ill-so-far/articleshow/40041465.cms


Over 250 people of Niphad village -- the taluka [similar to a county] headquarters [Nashik district, Maharashtra state] -- have been reported to be suffering from diarrhea, of whom 72 have been admitted to hospital since 4 Aug 2014. District health officials on Sunday said the department has declared an 'outbreak' of acute diarrheal disease at the village.

"As many as 72 people from Niphad were detected to be suffering from diarrhea and admitted to government hospitals, while 181 people who have been treated in out patient departments (OPD) were from Niphad and its surrounding villages," said Sushil Wakchaure, the district health officer (DHO).

All measures are being taken at the level of primary health centres to contain the spread of the disease, including measures to improve the water supply system.

"There are over 1500 people from the village or its surrounding areas who have been suffering from a number of ailments. The number of those suffering from diarrhea was 253. None of the patients were serious," said Dr Sahebrao Gawle of Niphad sub-civil hospital. Health officials have sounded an alert and medical teams have been rushed to the village to identify and treat those affected by the disease.

The officials said that though an outbreak had been declared locally, the final confirmation of the same would be done only after the DHO receives reports of stool samples sent to Pune. Officials are still trying to identify the cause, but primarily, this seems to be linked to the very old water supply line in Niphad that might have been punctured at more than one site, resulting in contaminated water.

[Byline: Abhilash Botekar]

